<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=9861239349932></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9861239349932><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/strategy/classes.html?class=12&mid=9861239349932>RE: race</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Apr 1st 7:18 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Just as a word of advice, Erudite magicians start off kill-on-sight with all Paineel residents, so it's not so easy as to just waltz in and start fighting in Paineel. You might get away with it if you don't turn in your newbie note, but you'll be robeless for a few levels if you do that.<br><br>If you want to fight in the Warrens, you'll be fine by the time you're at that level, so you can slip into Paineel with few problems. The guards look undead, but they can't see through invisibility, so just cast invisibility on yourself and run like the wind until you get well past the guards. Your level 4 pet just isn't good enough for dungeon fighting, and the entrance to the Warrens is a pretty hazzardous area for trains.<br><br>I never had a problem with night vision as an Erudite. At levels 1-4, I just used True North to find my way back to town, and after that my wisp stone, plus True North, plus Sense Summoned helped me get my bearings really easily. Also, most of the nice camp spots in Toxxulia are right by the zone wall or river, so they're easy to get to. And remember, once you hit level 16 you will never worry about night vision again.<br><br>But gnomes are pretty good magicians, too, and they're adorably cute, and Steamfont is such a nice zone up until you get Bind Affinity. After that, you can pretty much fight anywhere you want.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
