<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=98548196462108></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98548196462108><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/strategy/classes.html?class=12&mid=98548196462108>RE: Hey, I just have some questions</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Mar 24th 7:59 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>You can get a decent amount of experience and loot right in your own back yard hunting drakes and the occasional elemental beyond the windmills in Steamfont.<br><br>Around level 10 or so, go get yourself bound in Freeport and use invisibility to sneak through Nektalos Forest to Lavastorm. Excellent fighting there, and really good loot. The fire drakes drop putrid bile and gems; lava basilisks drop eggs and eyestalks which sell for several gold apiece. After level 12, your shielded, burned out pet should be able to take a beating from the rock dervishes. Use your weightless bags to hold the bricks of ore, which sell for 4gp to the gypsies in Lavastorm.<br><br>Most of the loot in Lavastorm is lightweight and stackable, so you can take the boat back to Ak'anon and sell to your guild merchants for better prices every couple of levels. Bloodstones are common gem drops here, so split the difference between merchant buy/sell price and auction them off to clerics and paladins.<br><br>If you can take out the occasional wandering fire goblin, they frequently drop soot hemlock, which sells for a pretty penny as well.<br><br>Most drakes and dervishes drop an average of 2gp; sometimes it's silver and copper, sometimes it's as high as 6gp. Imps and sprites are stingy; basilisks, elementals, and lava crawlers don't seem to have pockets but do drop gems or other loot.<br><br>A lot of high level players wander this zone on the way to the various dungeons, so you'll often sit down to meditate and stand up to find you've been gifted with some decent buffs by generous enchanters and druids.<br><br>The money and experience is comparable to fighting wisps (which don't drop the greater lightstones very often; maybe one drop in ten), and only the wandering elementals will give you trouble. All the other mobs are non-social and non-aggressive, so you can pick and choose what you fight fairly easily. Just stay away from the northern reaches, where the crocodiles will give you a run for your money if you get too close.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
