<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=98335264870321></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98335264870321><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/strategy/classes.html?class=12&mid=98335264870321>Pet situational uses</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?id=21128><span id= >Beetlebrow</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>53 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Feb 28th 4:30 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.32]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Kadthar for Beetlebrow here who only seems to know one element: muck.<br><br>I have found that each pet, at least those I have practiced with extensively, are definitely more useful than all the others in certain situations.  <br><br>The earth pet, for example, is a great pet for sheer tanking with its large hit points and ability to root.  It will keep the monsters off you and allow you to cast on them, or whatever you need to do.  It does seem to hit less often, and thus do less damage, though any given hit seems to do about as much as most of the other pets.  It also seems to regenerate slower than the others, though this may be simply a misconception due to the greater hit points involved (which may make it seem to heal slower).  <br>The weakness of this pet is that the relatively low overall damage it does and one's tendency to use direct damage when using it as a tank cause any creatures other than the one it's rooted to want to come after you.  This makes this pet most useful in taking down a single, though perhaps larger creature that it can fight, root and keep occupied while you blast it.<br><br>The fire pet, while having low hit points, heals very fast and does tremendous damage, including good normal attack damage, a damage shield, and a direct damage attack, for what is surely the highest damage of all the pets.  The low hit points prevent the fire pet from being very useful against higher level opponents, as they will tend to be killed quickly.  <br>However against multiple opponents of lower level, the fire pet is ideal.  They can fight multiple opponents at once and will be more likely to keep the creatures off you due to the large amount of damage they deal.  They are particularly good against multiple opponents, as their damage shield deals damage to any of the creatures that hit the pet, again keeping them off you.  This frees you up for occasional tanking for the pet, which he may need with his low hit points, or direct damage, since most creatures will still want to fight the pet, particularly if you are far away.<br><br>The water pet is often called the best of all the pets, but this is not strictly true.  While its decent ratings in all abilities, strngth, hit points, agility, and its great healing do make it a good all-around pet, that is different from the best pet.<br>The water pet is second to the fire pet in damage dealt, second to the earth pet in hit points, and has the best regeneration and has very high poison resistance.  This obviously makes it a good pet in situations where you expect to fight monsters with poison, but its decent all-around stats also give it the spot as probably the best pet to have if you don't know what you'll be facing.  It can be strong enough to face a single higher-level monster, or damaging enough to deal with multiple creatures, where its regeneration really comes in handy.<br><br>The air pet is the one I have the least experience with, so my comments on it are mostly restatements of the comments of others or extrapolations from the abilities the air pet is known to have.  The air pet in many ways is the worst-seeming pet, as it lacks the huge damage of the fire pet and the huge hit points of the earth pet, and doesn't make up for it with second-best status in both like the water pet.  However the air pet has some very unusual abilities that make it ideal in certain situations.  <br>First of all, the air pet has a stun spell that, as has often been said, makes it ideal against spellcasting mosnters by disrupting their casting.  Though all pets can do this by bashing, the air pet has more chances to do so, and with a good dexterity, will hit often with its bash in addition to its spell, providing a large amount of spell disruption.  Furthermore, air elementals can turn invisible which makes them a superior pet to any of the others in most dungeons, as pets have a tendency to get lost in dungeons, and when they finally die or find you, to bring large groups down on your head.  The air pet, being invisible, should minimize this issue (though, of course, still not making it go away completely).  As I have said, the air pet is my weakness at the moment, so I expect others could describe its strengths and weaknesses better.<br><br>I hope to hear replies to this post, and further comments on the situations which particular pets excel in.  Also, feel free to rate this or any posts.<br><br>Kadthar &lt;Divinity&gt;<br>Level 16 Gatecaller<br>Tholuxe Paells<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
